ce:section.ce:para:
The key point worth mentioning is that the 5-CDT from both plots (Fig. 4b and c) exhibited higher slopes than those of both TiO2 and 10-CDT. In mutual correlation with the specific capacitance, 1-CDH also showed higher slope value when compared to those of H2SO4, 0.5-CDH and 2-CDH (Fig. 4e and f). These results prove that the introduction of CDs in TiO2 electrode and H2SO4 electrolyte significantly enhanced various parameters, including the number of transferred electrons (n) and the surface coverage of the adsorbed species (

                              Γ

                        ) and/or the diffusion coefficient of the electroactive species (D0
                        ), as these parameters are in the slope values. In a brief conclusion, the CDs affected several crucial factors for charge transfer mechanisms through diffusion and adsorption processes, which reduced the series resistance and increased in the specific capacitance of the supercapacitors.

Consequently, the diffusion-controlled capacitance (Ci
                        ) can be calculated from Eq. (7). As illustrated in Table 3
                        , the outcomes show that the charge storage mechanism of pristine TiO2 electrode in 1 M H2SO4 electrolyte is eminently controlled by the surface-capacitive process (80.4%). Conversely, the contribution from the diffusion process is only 19.6%. The introduction of CDs in electrode and electrolyte distinctly raised the contribution from the diffusion-controlled process in charge storage. The 5-CDT in 1 M H2SO4 electrolyte produced the predominant charge storage contribution from the surface-controlled process (79.3%), but increasing the concentration to 2 M H2SO4 solution increased the diffusion-controlled process from 20.7% to 24.4%. Therefore, these results exhibited that the concentration of electrolyte is a critical factor that influences the charge storage mechanism and electrochemical performance. The 5-CDT in 1-CDH displayed the highest diffusion contribution of 42.8%, agreeing with the highest specific capacitance. These effects thus confirm with Cottrell’s and Randles-Sevcik’s analysis that the presence of CDs enhanced the proportion of diffusion-controlled process, driving to a higher specific capacitance.
